text.tspan: Kumar
I targeted an audience of an older demographic as they are more likely to vote (US
Census Bureau 2021). I did this by arguing that children need to be protected and by taking on
community values like family and safety. While this may miss the mark with young people who
do not have children and feel talked down to, it is right on track with what parents and
grandparents are concerned about. So, my poster is more likely to connect with older individuals,
and is therefore more likely to result in real-votes for the legal proposition it is supporting.
I used a casual tone to make the poster feel like it comes from neighbors instead of a
political organization. People are less likely to support a large organization that appears invading
their community in comparison to a community-led campaign, so it is important that the
advertisement comes off as being from concerned citizens. This framing is a trope of political
ads as they often claim to be from regular people even when they are put out by political
organizations. That being said, as my advertisement aims to create a law, I was sure to make it
sound formal enough that it is perceived as being well-thought-out.
I incorporated graphs to bring numerical evidence behind my proposition. As my
advertisement makes big claims about a problem many people are not aware of, it is crucial that
it backs up its claims with irrefutable facts. I included statistics from reputable governmental and
academic sources in engaging visuals that enable readers to see my numerical evidence without
reading the sentences that explain them. Furthermore, those interested in a detailed explanation
have the opportunity to read graph titles and captions that bring further credibility and detail to
the ad.
